# Code Style

## Flutter/Dart

- Follow Dart style guide conventions
- 2 spaces for indentation (not tabs)
- Prefer single quotes unless the string contains single quotes
- Trailing commas in multi-line collections and function calls
- Use `const` constructors when possible

## Line Breaking

- Break long lines at logical points (operators, commas)
- Each parameter on its own line when breaking function/constructor calls
- Align continuation lines with opening parenthesis
- Break long switch expressions: each case on its own line

## File Organization

- Import order: `dart:` → `package:` → relative imports
- Blank lines between import groups
- Alphabetical within each group

## Naming Conventions

- `camelCase` — variables, functions, methods
- `PascalCase` — classes, enums, typedefs
- `snake_case` — file names
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` — constants

## Variable Naming

- **Must** use descriptive names — not `e`, `i`, `x` (except simple loop counters)

```dart
// ❌ Bad
items.map((e) => e.toDomain())

// ✅ Good
items.map((item) => item.toDomain())
```

## Type Dispatch

- **Must** use `is` pattern matching for type dispatch — never `runtimeType` comparison
- **Must** use `final` for all local variables that are not reassigned

```dart
// ✅ Good
switch (this) {
  final FooDto dto => dto.toDomain(),
  final BarDto dto => dto.toDomain(),
  _ => null,
};

// ❌ Bad
switch (runtimeType) {
  const (FooDto) => (this as FooDto).toDomain(),
  const (BarDto) => (this as BarDto).toDomain(),
  _ => throw UnsupportedError('...'),
};
```

## Documentation

- `///` for public API dartdoc comments
- Include examples for complex functions

## Formatting

- **Must** use `dart format` with a line length of **120** characters (configured in `analysis_options.yaml` as `page_width: 120`)
- **Must not** manually wrap lines shorter than 120 characters unless it improves readability
- **Must** end every file with exactly one newline character — include on creation, don't fix later

## Security

- Never commit API keys or sensitive data
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Validate all user inputs
- Use secure storage for sensitive data

## Git

- Clear, descriptive commit messages (conventional commit format)
- Focused, atomic commits
- Use `.github/pull_request_template.md` for PR descriptions (don't create the file, put content in chat)
